NO. The proposed patch attempts to fix the bug by filtering neighbors to keep only the minimum edge cost per neighbor before pushing them onto the heap, but this does not address the fundamental flaw in the original algorithm. The core issue is that the algorithm prematurely marks nodes as "queued" and never revisits them even if a cheaper path is found later, violating the principle of Dijkstra's algorithm which requires updating tentative distances and re-adding nodes to the priority queue when a better path is discovered. Simply filtering neighbors by minimum edge cost does not allow the algorithm to reconsider nodes with improved costs, so it will still fail on graphs where a cheaper path to a node is found after a more expensive one has already been enqueued. Therefore, the patch does not correctly fix the bug and the algorithm remains incorrect for the described scenarios.
